                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d204">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4/1348: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Acting Chairman of the American Delegation (<persName corresp="#p_GHS1"
                            type="to">Gibson</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-20T13:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 20, 1932—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>188. Since talking with you over the telephone I have again studied the
                    resolution as a whole with its most recent modifications and wish to
                    congratulate you on the elements of strength and the direct relationship to the
                    President’s plan which you have successfully retained. I realize fully that you
                    have been up against a determined effort to whittle away the effectiveness of
                    the President’s plan and do not wish you to feel from some criticisms of detail
                    I may have made over the telephone this morning that I underestimate the real
                    measure of success you have had.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
